<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,541,1414,1440]" pageId="7" pageNumber="549">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,330,1414,1440]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="549">Piona sejugata</emphasis>
K.O. Viets, 
<number box="[482,541,1414,1440]" pageId="7" pageNumber="549" value="1953.0">1953</number>
</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,1485,1654]" pageId="7" pageNumber="549">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,340,1485,1510]" pageId="7" pageNumber="549">Species incerta.</emphasis>
Since the original description of the species, it has only been reported from 
<collectingCountry box="[1255,1436,1485,1510]" name="Netherlands" pageId="7" pageNumber="549">the Netherlands</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Davids" box="[158,311,1521,1546]" pageId="7" pageNumber="549" refString="Davids, C. (1979) De Watermijten (Hydrachnellae) van Nederland. Levenswijze en voorkomen. Wetenschappelijke mededelingen van de Koninklijke Nederlandse Natuurhistorische Vereniging, 132, 1 - 78." type="journal article" year="1979">
Davids 
<number box="[252,311,1522,1546]" pageId="7" pageNumber="549" value="1979.0">1979</number>
</bibRefCitation>
, Smit &amp; Van der 
<bibRefCitation author="Hammen" box="[535,712,1522,1546]" pageId="7" pageNumber="549" refString="Smit, H. &amp; Van der Hammen, H. (2000) Atlas van de Nederlandse watermijten. Nederlandse Faunistische Mededelingen, 13, 1 - 272. [in Dutch, with English summaries]" type="journal article" year="2000">
Hammen 
<number box="[651,712,1522,1546]" pageId="7" pageNumber="549" value="2000.0">2000</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). After studying the 
<typeStatus box="[965,1066,1521,1546]" pageId="7" pageNumber="549">holotype</typeStatus>
, it must be concluded that the description of the species is based on an aberrant, intersexual specimen. The third leg of the male 
<typeStatus box="[1272,1370,1557,1582]" pageId="7" pageNumber="549">holotype</typeStatus>
lacks the grasping sixth segment, but instead this segment is just bowed. The species should therefore be considered a monstrosity. The description of the female matches the description of 
<taxonomicName box="[933,1053,1629,1653]" class="Arachnida" family="Pionidae" genus="Piona" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="7" pageNumber="549" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="alpicola">
<emphasis box="[933,1053,1629,1653]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="549">P. alpicola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
